\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs24 
What you have written is very good (reminds me of many fantasy stories) and a lot of it I think is fine to remain as is. There are some things however that I do disagree with, but short of re-writing the whole story as you have 
written it I will just mention the points I believe need changing in a little detail so we can discuss these.
\par 
\par Ok, it seems we cannot stick with the original Mecarro and make headway. Very well.
\par I am happy with him being a mercenary. His motives however, something which have
\par ever been a stumbling point are very unclear. It is mentioned that the Cvin seized
\par his land and holdings, yet there is no mention of any enmity towards the Cvin. How
\par could there not be? Instead he seems to wish to kill poor innocent people and drive them into slavery for his own profits. 
\par 
\par Mecarro need not be an angel, but he need not be a ruthless villain either. I think there is no need to have such a dark angle on h
is past. I quite like that prodding finger provided by the people of Enamareth, perhaps in the beginning he was rebellious but had no direction, a direction that Ninine etc provided. 
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 Ok so his origins, I suggest the following:
\par }{\fs24 
\par Stripped of his family pos
sessions of land and title, his father executed for "treasonous thoughts" he was angry, but yet young to understand the ways of the world. His father had ordered his arms tutor to guide him should something happen to him, as he feared his fate. His arms t
utor taught him to control his anger and also the ways of combat in which he excelled at in a very short time. He made up his mind early to avenge his fathers death, somehow.
\par 
\par For funding you suggest his first conquest was a bunch of Jlen potters. I suggest
 that this makes little sense. I think it would be much more feasible that his first act was one of banditry, striking at a lesser travelling cvin nobleman and his wife and escort of 3. His first chance to shed blood, Mecarro slew all but one man and the 
woman himself, ordering her hanged for her crimes against his family. He then sold their belongings for funding, at this stage trying to remain as anonymous as possible.
\par With the funds he was able to quietly hire more men etc.
\par 
\par Similar to as you mentioned i
n your note, news of this bandit group grew as more and more Cvin nobles etc were reported dead or missing. No one however knew his identity, and he was thought to be a simple bandit, of course the guard was doubled etc. I would suggest it was then that h
e
 passed through Enarmareth. One of his men said too much over a beer and was overheard by an off duty Cvin guardsman, the fight then ensued left many dead, and had Mecarro and his men fleeing into the forests, where they made their camp. This is where the
 people of Enamareth send Ninine and perhaps 20 young men to aid and guide Mecarro. Before this his aspirations had been mindless revenge but with Ninine's "guidance" he quickly was soon brought to envision something greater. 
\par 
\par He continued his ways, quite a substantial force now of perhaps 40 men, able to waylay travelers with little or no bloodshed. The nobles hanged, the possessions sold and the rest told that if their faces were seen again they would be killed.
\par 
\par Enter the other Rehan and Malandrin lords 
as you suggested, offering their support. They then betray him when he refuses their support (though why would he refuse something he could use like this?, seems weird) (it does allow them to betray him then and make a nice story I guess) they betray him 
a
nd a squad of fifty cvin (the enamareth garrison) ambushes him. Mecarro fights like a whirlwind etc etc, inspiring his men and they win the day though with heavy casualties, their numbers halved. He executes as many of the betraying nobles as he can get h
i
s hands on (aka William Wallace). They get an amount of weapons from the corpses, and are able to fund more mercenaries. Some also hearing of the great warrior Mecarro even seek him out, pledging themselves to fight for him. But he was still little more t
hen a mercantile bandit.
\par 
\par Having bested the Cvin militia though, things were not going to get easier. The escaping men sending afar for help. 
\par 
\par This is where a division of the Cvin army came along, he used the burning water technique, and won the day again.
 Stories of his bravery and skill did not go unnoticed and he raged across the land like a fire, his first undertaking Enamareth (at the direction of Ninine of course), he armed any and all who wished to fight for him, greeting them personally etc.
\par 
\par Meanwh
ile the response to the call for help earlier was surprisingly small, the contented Cvin lords in their own environs not believing anyone could possibly threaten them, and only a token force was sent. Certainly nothing that could crush the ever growing th
reat Mecarro provided.
\par 
\par His first major conquest was Cora'Kan (made that up, it doesn\rquote t exist now) a large city
\par with trade importance. 
\par 
\par I don\rquote t think setting fire to the legs of the Ximmerin is a feasible way of winning a battle though. It just seems a bit
 weird. I would suggest that his invention of the catapult resulted in a surprisingly easy victory as they stood outside bow range firing flaming rocks into the city. Those fleeing from the city ruthlessly cut down, and given no chance of escape or quarte
r. (Even women and children of nobles hanged if you like).
\par 
\par He kept going, eventually sacking the Cvin capital of Il'Cora'Sentar, and driving the remaining Cvin lords and their army west into the forests.
\par 
\par Mecarro always the mercenary was not much of a politician, the courts becoming too dangerous for him etc, Ninine convincing him to settle to Enamareth and do as he did best, train soldiers and hire himself out to the highest bidder, from which he made a f
ine living. (Also Mecarros Wildcats sounds a bit gay, perhaps Mecarro's Ravens)
\par 
\par Ru'Psarn grew as an almost mercenary barracks in the beginning, to become more of a town, though it was well fortified as you might expect. Any were welcomed there whether they
 wished to be trained to fight or not, the protection of Mecarro extend to all (but the Cvin of course).
\par 
\par Nowadays the mercenary tradition of Ru'Psarn still exists, the town the home of the famous Ravens, a well trained group of mercenaries whose exploits are widely known.  
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 Problems I see with this:
\par }{\fs24 
\par Maintaining the role-play. With the mercs making up a large part of Ru'Psarn us as imms will need to do a lot of work keeping the mercenary aspect obvious to the players. We certainly cant stand idle, unless
 we make pcs take on key roles within the mercenary society. The players will look to the mercenaries reactions to a variety of situations to know how to react themselves. This will prove quite difficult to manage I feel.
\par 
\par Clans trying to hire these mercen
aries, we will have to allow it, thus leaving the town itself vulnerable. A smart clan leader will hire the mercenaries to fight some useless war and attack it while they are gone, take it, and defend it against the mercenaries. The only saving grace bein
g that the town is not especially wealthy, and perhaps not worth that much trouble at the expense of the clan in question.
\par 
\par Also no magic is mentioned at all. Do they have any magicians nowadays? If they don\rquote t it is likely they fear magic, and this could po
se a HUGE problem as to their strength. Send a couple of powerful mages at a superstitious force and you shatter them.
\par 
\par Nothing is mentioned of the time of madness etc. Before this it is likely that the mercenary nature was preserved, but more to protect a
gainst banditry I would suggest. No wars as such. With the madness things got thrown into disarray, but the mercs still stay fine and dandy? Seems a bit weird, you would think some things would have changed. Perhaps they establish some code back in Mecarr
o's daughters days which stays with them and helps them remain together in the troubled times. I\rquote m not suggesting a code of Knightly Chivalry, but something suitable.
\par 
\par The town needs to be pretty open too, it cant be locked down at all, with strict access e
tc. The town proper would not be hugely guarded, and what would the mercs do for pay when there are no wars to fight? I would suggest they are only paid if they work for the town guard too, they are given meals and lodging if they train with the mercs, bu
t not paid unless there is a battle. Free training though is probably worth it.
\par 
\par Having a mercenary band protect a town suggests that they do it pretty much for free, and also suggests that either
\par a) They are so many in number that they need the entire town just to "camp" in or
\par b) They are not just in it for the money.
\par I would think the mercs would stick mainly to one area of the town with the barracks and training grounds etc, the town an almost separate thing. But then why protect it? This would suggest so
me kind of tax paid by the citizens of Ru'Psarn to the mercs. Do we want new players having to pay a tax? I\rquote m sure we can code it, realistic but harsh perhaps.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 Conclusion: 
\par }{\fs24 I have suggested a few changes should we stick with the story Torill has written
 as what is to happen. My feelings however are that we need some kind of collaboration between the original story and Torill's suggestion, I think this can be easily achieved. The problem I have stems from Ru'Psarns make-up now and post-coming. I have no 
p
roblem with it being a place founded on a mercenary background, and this would work quite well all the way up until the coming and the madness. But I would suggest here we change tack and come up with a design that covers all the bases that need covering 
b
etter. A more lock tight leadership for the town, that requires as little imm involvement directly as possible, which is strong militarily, and detailed in a story sense. I think that with the new existence of magic, if Ru'Psarn does not move to bring in 
magic in some way shape or form it would cease to exist.
\par 
\par Sorry this took so long to write, I am without ISP, have been working a lot, have exams, the world cup cricket was on (Australia won, YAY!) and Tims car (transport to the nearest computer with net access) was broken for a while. (Excuses ended)
\par 
