\par Mecarro and Ru\rquote Psarn:
\par 
\par The origin:
\par A young boy escaped the law visited upon his father and his father holdings. His noble father executed for \'93treasonous thoughts\'94, Mecarro was forced to flee Ru\rquote 
Imer with only a few loyal retainers, his arms tutor amongst them. Angered and scared by the prospects this presented for him, Mecarro sought refuge wherever he could fin
d it, and he was quickly forgotten by his fathers killers. He decided early to avenge his fathers death, excelling quickly in the ways of combat thanks to his tutor.
\par 
\par The funding:
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par The first place Mecarro struck was at a settlement a little up the coast from Ru\rquote 
Imer.  With four men following him, two of them drafted from Enamareth, his old weapons teacher and a hired hand following them on promises of a share of the loot, they struck against a family of Jlen potters living close to where they took their 
clay out.  Striking at night, they killed the oldest and the youngest, and took away two families of skilled crafters, 7 Jlen women and 5 Jlen men.  A swift robbery of a young Cvin woman out recklessly riding alone got Ninie a dress that made her look the
 part, and she took the string of slaves to the market in Cora\rquote 
Kan where she had a sweet profit.  The slaves had all had their tongues cut out before the sale, exept a few of the youngest children, considered too young to know what had happened to them.
\par \tab With the profit Mecarro could hire more hands, and Ninie spied out settlements of a similar kind.  Always choosing the vulnerable J\rquote 
len craftsmen, living apart and considered thieves and untrustworthy by their neighbours, Mecarro soon had a large band of hir
ed soldiers.  They built a camp in Enamareth, in the forest of the hillside, hidden from the casual eye, but with an excellent view over the roads into and out of the village.
\par 
\par 
\par Enamareth, the origin:
\par There were seven farms, prosperous and beautiful sprawling in the fertile valley of Enamareth.  The generosity of the land made the people living there strong and healthy.  It wasn\rquote t particularly isolated either, four days of easy travel and you
\rquote d reach the coast and the village of Ru\rquote Imer, six days in the other direction got you to the larger center of Cora\rquote Kan, both well-known and busy centers in the time of the Cvin empire.
\par 
\par In the time of the Cvin empire, the Rehan of Enamareth suffered greatly from the taxes, their sons drafted to the army, to fight for and serve the Cvin, their daughters \'93hired\'94
 as maids and returning with their bellies bulging over the seed of Cvin lordlin
gs.  When the young Mecarro passed through, the people of the valley of Enamareth supported his rebellion, seeing in the ruthlessness vendetta of the youth the weapon that could give them their revenge as well as their own.  And so they sent the loveliest
 
of the girls, Ninie, the half-breed of the Cvin lordling Gorath Siomain, to Mecarro, making certain he was well pleased with his stay in Enamareth, and that he would wish to return.  Ninie had all the beauty of her Cvin father, and all the earthy craftine
s
s of her Rehan mother, a woman with hair like spun gold, eyes like violet lakes, and a mind like a stalking cat, as swift and dangerous.  When Mecarro went on, she went with him, and she swiftly started putting the plans of the people or Enamareth into li
fe.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par The idea:
\par As the band and Mecarro\rquote s wealth grew, so did his reputation.  And soon his father\rquote s friends came to \'93remember\'94 the young man they had so conveniently forgotten all about when his father was executed for \'93treasonous thoughts\'94
 and the wealth of the house was taken over by the Cvin, together with Mecarro\rquote 
s family and the land.  Finding themselves pressed from all sides as the Cvin started taking over more and more of the wealthy old Malandrin houses, they came with offerings of their economic 
support and their acceptance and protection, if he would suport them in the fight against the Cvin.  Ninie quickly disillusioned Mecarro about the measure of support, and tried to get him from it.  When he refused, the old \'93friends\'94
 sold him to the Cvin au
thorities for the murder of the young woman supplying the clothes Ninie had worn at that first auction.  And the people of Enamareth, who also wanted Mecarro to fight the Cvin, not drag lawless men into their valley, helpfully pointed into the forest when
 a small troup of Cvin came to capture Mecarro.
\par \tab To get away, Mecarro had to kill the Cvin, and he slaughtered four men, Ninie getting a fitth who was trying to stab him in the back, his old weaponsmaster killing two.  Now he had to leave Enamareth, and he 
told his men to meet him in the forests at the west edge of the Ru\rquote Psarn plains.  They met him there, but so did a division of the Cvin army, to aresst him.  It is in this fight that the famous \'93burning water\'94
 technique was applied to fighting figting hors
ed men for the first time.  Seeming to retreat across a river, across a wide, shallow ford, Mecarro teased the riders into the water.  The moment the horses were in the water, a flaming arrow was shot at them and the oil that had been pored on the water f
urther upriver ignited in an inferno of flames.  The disorganised riders were easily picked off, and the weapons passed out to those who came to follow Mecarro in the days following.
\par \tab It was soon clear that Mecarro would not have peace until he was dead or 
the Cvin were thrown.  And so his long series of battles started.  He raged like a fire across the land, arming any who swore to fight for him, killing those who refused.  With Ninie at his side like a furious angel, Lu\rquote 
Tamor bent before his weapons-skills
 and ruthlessness, coupled with her intelligence and strategic advise.  It was Ninie who started to make sure Mecarro would welcome personally everybody who wanted to join him, taking their hand, saying something personal, something Ninie or his officers 
h
ad supplied in advance.  And soon the rumour grew that he refused nobody, that there were people of all races in his ranks, and that he would fight to end the long, heavy oppression of the Cvin empire.  This made more and more swarm to his army, and when 
he rode out before the gates of (supply name of important Cvin city here) it was with the fields about the gates covered with people singing of the end of the Cvin empire,and the freedom of all men.
\par 
\par The fall of an empire:
\par The songs about the red fields of Emein are not quite true - there was very little blood shed among Mecarro\rquote 
s ranks.  A nest of young Ximmerin had ben spotted in the towers of the west side of the city.  On a day with wind from the west, the young ximmerin hunting for fish in a pond just o
utside the city gates were captured.  From their legs were tied oiled cloth, which were then put fire to.  Ximmerin, being related to the salamanders living close to volcanoes, can tolerate flames, but they will be burned.  And all of the flying lizards o
n Lu\rquote Tamor tend to return to their nests immediately in case of danger.  So the west towers were ignited and the flames soon skipped from tower to tower, the city flaring into flame.
\par \tab Fleeing from the madness of the city streets, the people of (supply centr
al city here) poured out the gate.  And so it was that the red fields of Emain received its grizly sacrifice and the name was justified, with the blood of helpless Cvin, children, women and elderly.  A poorly organised group of soldiers tried to protect t
he innocents, but they were swiftly murdered, their gestures of surrender ignored by the angry peasants and craftsmen following Mecarro.  
\par \tab At the fall of the empire, Mecarro as the only figure of unity was kept on with the army in (central city) by the cou
ncil swiftly collected by the politicians of the different races.  Ninie kept making sure he was seen with people of all races, her own Cvin appearance calming the few surviving Cvin.  As Lu\rquote 
Tamor settled back into the new power-patterns, court soon became
 a dangerous place for Mecarro.  Ninie suggested that he do what he knew.. Train soldiers and hire them to the factor with the most money.  And so he returned to Enamareth, to the old camp in the forest.
\par 
\par Somewhat happy for a while after:
\par At the mouth of the Enamareth valley, with a view over the Ru\rquote 
Psarn plains, Mecarro set up his estates, settling with his men.  He built not a manor, but a garrison, and his troops became a mercenary troop.  For the next 20 years, he led his men on campaigns for the highes
t bidder.  And those who could afford to hire Mecarro\rquote s Wildcats were almost guarateed to win - to the point that several disputes were settled peacefully once he showed up at the battlefield.
\par \tab He had a horde of children with Ninie and an assorted number of mistresses.  His own prodigy were of varied appearance, and the men of his troops brought home their women and children to the place they soon spoke of only as Ru\rquote 
Psarn.  And so a town grew, with all the crafts supporting a standing army, the wealth of Lu\rquote Tamor flowing into the town, but soon enough back into the land again by way of the pockets of the mercenary soldiers.  Ru\rquote 
Psarn has little to offer but a fertile farmland, and apart from the mercenaries, there was little wealth in the area.
\par 
\par Mecarro\rquote s end:
\par A stray arrow became his undoing.  It should have been a very easy job, but a nervous and over eager bow-man released a shot against him as he rode out into the field to parley.  The bards say that his last words as he died were: \'93Thus, I give my own b
lood to fertile this earth - in the sacrifice i have led so many into.\'94
  Other bards tell of how Ninie, his wife showed up close to him, suddenly, her golden hair like a cloud about her face to gather his final breath into her mouth in a kiss, then to have
 him taken from the field.  Others tell of the way it started to rain, or the way the temperature fell at the moment he died...  But what ever truly happened - Mecarro was dead.  And so ended the life of one of the most ruthless men in the history of Lu
\rquote Tamor.
\par 
\par Ru\rquote Psarn\rquote s future:
\par Founded from the followers to a motley mercenary troop, Ru\rquote Psarn kept growing under the wealth still flowing into the city.  Ninie set Mecarro\rquote s oldest daughter to lead the troops, and she again founded a college for the training o
f soldiers, one which became famous throughout Lu\rquote Tamor.
